# Project Title
Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) of a Persian BERT Model for Named Entity
Recognition
1. Project Objective
The goal of this project is to fine-tune a pre-trained Persian language model using ParameterEfficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT), specifically the LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation) method, for the
task of Named Entity Recognition (NER).
The task is formulated as binary token classification, where:
• Label 1 → Token is part of a named entity (person name)
• Label 0 → Token is not a named entity
2. Dataset Description
The dataset consists of multiple .txt files, where each file contains token-level annotations in the
following format:
• Each line contains one token and its binary NER label.
• Sentences are separated by empty lines.
• Labels were already provided in binary format (0/1), so no additional label mapping was
required.
3. Model and Tokenizer
We selected the following pre-trained Persian language model from Hugging Face:
• Model: HooshvareLab/bert-fa-base-uncased
• Architecture: BERT
• Task Type: Token Classification
• Number of Labels: 2 (entity / non-entity)
The corresponding tokenizer was loaded to ensure consistency between text processing and model
inputs.4. Data Preprocessing
4.1 Reading the Dataset
All text files in the dataset directory were read and combined.
For each sentence:
• Tokens were stored as a list of words.
• Labels were stored as a list of integers (0 or 1).
4.2 Tokenization and Label Alignment
Since BERT uses subword tokenization, some words are split into multiple sub-tokens.
To correctly train the model:
• Tokenization was performed with is_split_into_words=True
• Labels were aligned using word_ids()
• Sub-tokens inherited the label of the original word
• Special tokens were assigned the label -100 so they are ignored during loss computation
This step is essential for correct token-level supervision.
5. Dataset Splitting
The dataset was split into three subsets:
This allows:
• Model training on the training set
• Hyperparameter monitoring on the validation set
• Final unbiased evaluation on the test set
6. Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT)
6.1 LoRA Configuration
LoRA was applied to the attention layers (query and value) with the following configuration:
• Rank (r) = 8
• LoRA scaling factor (alpha) = 32
• Dropout = 0.1
• Task type = TOKEN_CLS
7. Model TrainingThe model was trained using Hugging Face’s Trainer API with:
• Mixed-precision training (fp16)
• Mini-batch training
• Validation performed periodically during training
• Cross-entropy loss at the token level
The training objective was to correctly classify each token as entity (1) or non-entity (0).
8. Model Evaluation
8.1 Evaluation Metrics
The trained model was evaluated on the test set using standard NER metrics at the token level:
• Precision
• Recall
• F1-score
Special tokens and padding tokens (label -100) were excluded from evaluation.
8.2 Results Interpretation
The evaluation results show that the model is capable of:
• Identifying named entities in Persian news-style text
• Distinguishing entity tokens from non-entity tokens
• Generalizing beyond the training data
The LoRA-based fine-tuning achieved competitive performance while training only a small
fraction of the model parameters.
9. Challenges and Solutions
9.1 Tokenization Alignment
Challenge: Subword tokenization complicates label assignment.
Solution: Used word-level alignment via word_ids() and ignored non-word tokens.
9.2 Resource Constraints
Challenge: Full fine-tuning of BERT is expensive.
Solution: Used PEFT (LoRA) to significantly reduce trainable parameters.9.3 Colab Library Conflicts
Challenge: Version inconsistencies in Colab.
Solution: Used stable training arguments and avoided version-dependent features.
10. Conclusion
In this project, we successfully fine-tuned a Persian BERT model for Named Entity Recognition
using Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (LoRA).
Key achievements:
• Implemented a complete NER pipeline
• Reduced training cost via PEFT
• Achieved reliable token-level entity detection
• Built a scalable and efficient training framework
This project demonstrates the practical effectiveness of PEFT methods for adapting large
language models to low-resource and domain-specific NLP tasks.
